<head>
<title>Duplantier: Welfare Reform/CA & IL -- 6/19/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</b><BR>
          

<i>
Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
June 19, 1996<br><p></i>
<h2>Welfare Reform/CA & IL</h2>
<i><blockquote>
<P>
With Congress talking about bloc-granting welfare money    
back to the states, some good ideas are starting to circulate.
</I></Blockquote><P>

There are nearly three million Californians receiving Aid to    
Families with Dependent Children (known as AFDC),    
roughly two million of whom have been on the dole for more    
than two years. "To a large extent, California's history of high    
AFDC benefits is responsible for the entrenched cycle of    
poverty that many now decry," say Sally Pipes and Katherine    
Post of the Pacific Research Institute in San Francisco. A    
new proposal by the California Department of Social    
Services is designed to break that "cycle of poverty" by    
substantially reducing benefits.   
   <p>
"Benefit levels would be lowered and one standard payment    
set," say Pipes and Post in the May issue of Alternatives in    
Philanthropy, published by the Capital Research Center.    
"Welfare would not pay more than work." This "flat grant"    
would not be affected by "any increase in the number of    
adults or children in the household." Benefits would be    
available for a limited time only. "The grant would eliminate    
eligibility requirements that make aid available only when    
one parent is deceased, disabled, missing, or unemployed,"    
say Pipes and Post. "Eligibility would instead be based on a    
simple income and asset test, as well as on the presence of a    
child under 18 years of age."   
   <p>
In spite of these promising proposals, California has been    
"fundamentally unable to respond to the particularities of    
individual cases. Herein lies an opportunity for philanthropic    
alternatives," say Pipes and Post, who like to stress "the    
importance of private efforts that are successfully addressing    
the critical and massive problem of repairing the damage    
done by the welfare state. Private programs offer powerful,    
individual-oriented approaches that no government initiative    
can match."   
   <p>
Joseph Bast of the Heartland Institute in Palatine, Illinois    
argues that welfare reforms in his state don't go far enough,    
and consist mainly of "throwing good money after bad and    
reshuffling bureaucracies." .In 1994, the state's Governor    
proposed "a $5 billion-a-year state-run health maintenance    
organization." In 1996, the Governor proposed "creating a    
welfare super-agency by merging seven cabinet-level    
agencies and many other boards, commissions, and    
programs."   
   <p>
Bast argues that different reforms "could generate much    
greater benefits more quickly." He calls for "health-care    
vouchers that would give the needy a wider choice of medical    
providers and insurers." He proposes that the care of abused    
and neglected children be turned over "to private agencies    
that have a better track record of placing children into safe    
and stable homes." And he suggests that AFDC payments be    
limited to two years and that the state "remove from the rolls    
all those who fail to report to state offices when told to do so"    
for job training and referrals.   
   <p>
The great thing about America is that our 50 states give us    
the chance to address problems in different ways. Welfare is    
a big problem, and we need all the good ideas we can get.   

<P>
<center># # # # #</center>
<P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




