<head>
<title>Duplantier: World Heritage Areas -- 8/8/96</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#fffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><p><br>
<b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</B><br>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
August 8, 1996</i><br><p>
<h2>WORLD HERITAGE AREAS</h2>

<i>Did you know that the United Nations has sovereign control over 
Yellowstone Park? That's right, the UN, for all practical purposes, owns 
Yellowstone National Park!</i>
<p>
World-famous Yellowstone Park in Montana was visited by UN officials 
last fall, but they weren't there on vacation! Tom Deweese of the 
American Policy Center reports that these internationalist bureaucrats 
were "inspecting a site for a proposed gold mine . . . located on property 
outside of the Yellowstone National Park boundaries." In a recent issue of 
his group's newsletter, called Insider's Report, Deweese revealed what 
these world-governing wannabes were up to. "Radical environmentalists 
who oppose the mine development deliberately brought the UN into the 
debate in an attempt to stop it," he explained. "The decision of the UN 
site inspectors will determine if the mine may be developed. Their 
decision will end the debate."<p>

You heard correctly. This isn't some paranoid, futuristic fantasy. It's real, 
and it's happening right now. The UN is deciding whether or not 
American citizens have the right to put their own property to productive 
use. "What does the United Nations have to do with determining how 
land is used inside United States territory?" you ask. Deweese provides 
the shocking answer. "The United Nations," he says, "has sovereign 
control of Yellowstone Park."<p>

According to Deweese, radical environmentalists "invoked a little known 
treaty called the World Heritage Convention in order to involve the 
United Nations in an internal United States dispute. Jimmy Carter, in 
1978, signed the treaty and thereby designated Yellowstone a World 
Heritage Site. Now the United Nations has ultimate say in what happens 
to the park." Though not on park land, the site of the proposed mine 
happens to fall into the treaty-mandated "buffer zone."<p>

"There are several more World Heritage Sites within U.S. borders," 
observes Deweese. And, if you're not scandalized already, you will be, 
when you hear what two of them are: the Statue of Liberty in New York 
harbor and Independence Hall in Philadelphia! "That's right," says 
Deweese; "the United Nations controls the spot where America's 
Founding Fathers created our nation." In other words, authority over the 
two most famous symbols of our freedom has been ceded to an 
organization that seeks to destroy that freedom.<p>

"The World Heritage Convention is just one of a series of treaties that the 
United States has signed in the past few decades that grant control to the 
United Nations over U.S. law," Deweese points out. "Most of these 
treaties now have programs already in place to grab U.S. soil. And son e 
of these programs are much worse than just taking our nation's 
landmarks. Some have targeted all of the private property in the nation. 
That means your home." Perhaps the worst offender is the UN 
Convention on Biological Diversity, which, Tom Deweese charges, "lays 
down the plans for a 'reversal' of the process of civilization, ultimately 
overseeing the herding of people into pre-selected, isolated enclaves, 
while the rest of America becomes vast wilderness."<p>

<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>
<p><p></blockquote></blockquote><p><br>
