<html> 
<head> 
<title>Duplantier: Special Ed: Kids go in, Don't come out -- 8/28/96</title> 
</head> 
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg"> 
<blockquote><blockquote> 
<a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a> 
<b>Behind the Headlines</b><br> 
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.</i><br> 
<a href="http://www.townhall.com/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F. R. Duplantier</a><br> 
 <i> September 12, 1996</i><p> 
 
<h2> Environmental Economics </h2><p>


<i>The free market can protect the environment far better than any government can, so why not take advantage of it?<i><p>



People will take care of the environment voluntarily if they have sufficient incentive for doing so. Property rights provide that incentive. "A property rights strategy works through incentives; government intervention relies on commands," says Joseph Bast of the Heartland Institute, co-author of a new book called Eco-Sanity, A CommonSense Guide to Environmentalism. "Ownership leads to better stewardship. We tend to take better care of things we own than of things we only rent or borrow," says Bast. "Natural resources, therefore, are better cared for if they are owned by the people who use them." Not surprisingly, governments tend to prefer a coercive approach, which requires a monitoring system and "an apparatus to punish those who attempt to evade the commands."<p>

For governments, of course, coercion can be an end in itself. The sincere environmentalist, however, has no excuse for succumbing to the totalitarian temptation, once he realizes that compulsion is counterproductive. "Pollution problems occur where rights are not defined and enforced," says Bast. "When things are privately owned, the civil justice system keeps us from invading or damaging them. But, when they are owned in common . . . we are often driven by competition with others to exploit them quickly and with little regard for their future value. The result is often pollution, unsustainable rates of development, and endangerment of wildlife."<p>

The free exchange of the free market "can help solve environmental problems," says Bast. "Transferable property rights enable those who value a resource most highly to bid it away from those who value it less. Potential buyers -for example, nonprofit organizations and clubs devoted to conservation -- can use their property rights to purchase or lease land, reward good stewardship, or purchase covenants that restrict allowable uses of land. Such exchanges reveal the true cost of protecting the environment and ensure that this cost is shared by those who value the environment most."<p>

Because they do not operate according to free-market principles, governments inevitably harm the environment. "Government officials seeks to expand their budgets and authority by delivering short-term benefits to special interest groups," says Bast. "Because they do not own the resources they manage, these officials are unlikely to manage them for maximum asset value." Government' i monopoly status prevents it from comparing "its own efficiency to that of competing organizations. As a result, government agents cannot know how good a job they are doing -- or how much harm they are causing."<p>

The free market encourages efficiency, and that's good for the environment. ''Efficiency means producing the most output with the least input," says Joseph Bast. "Over time, a system that rewards efficiency will also tend to produce less pollution than one that tolerates inefficiency.'' Governments, on the other hand, are notoriously inefficient, and their inefficiency leads to waste and pollution. Environmentalists without hidden agendas should recognize the superiority of the free-market approach.<p>
<center> # # # # # # #</center><p> 
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit  
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free- 
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free  
