<head>
<title>Behind the Headlines</title>
<center>
<h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</h4>  
 <i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.  <br>
 F.R. Duplantier <br>
 September 29, 1995  <br>
  </i><hr>

<h2>Educators Attack Family Values  </h2></center>
 
An education expert says that "challenges from conservative citizen  
groups objecting to particular instructional strategies and materials" are  
hampering efforts "to make fundamental changes in public schooling "  <p>
  
  
Writing in the September 1993 issue of Phi Delta Kappan, Indiana  
University professor of education Martha McCarthy tipped off her  
colleagues to a new trend in parental protests against teaching materials.   
"Until the late 1970s the targets were usually individual books," she  
observed. "While the list of individual books under attack continues to  
grow. recent protests -- often orchestrated by national conservative  
groups -- are more likely to focus on entire textbook series and  
components of the instructional program." <p> 
  
That means that pet theories and vested interests are at stake. Take, for  
instance the Whole Language approach to reading. McCarthy noted that  
"the most widely challenged textbook series" at that time was Harcourt  
Brace Jovanovich's 10-volume anthology Impressions, which uses the  
Whole language method. "Most of the challenges focus on the series'  
subject matter rather than on its pedagogical approach," she conceded.  
"but the controversy associated with Impressions may have implications  
for the future of Whole-Language instruction."  <p>
  
McCarthy reported that conservatives have also attacked the Quest  
curriculum for teaching relativism and disrespect for parental authority,  
the Tactics for Thinking program for teaching New Age beliefs, and   
Outcome Based Education for teaching hardly anything. She noted that  
"instruction pertaining to values clarification, self-esteem, multicultural  
education, evolution, AIDS education, and global education are being  
contested as anti-Christian, anti-American, or other vise inappropriate."  
But the meddling doesn't stop there, McCarthy continued. "Several  
instructional strategies currently touted in the education literature, such as  
collaborative learning and thematic instruction, are being challenged  
because they shift to students some of the responsibility that was formerly  
lodged with the teacher."<p>  
  
Such challenges, McCarthy warned her peers, "call into question some of  
the basic assumptions of school restructuring initiatives," thereby posing  
"far more serious threats to efforts to improve the public school program  
than do challenges to individual novels." What's more, she added, "the  
success rate of those initiating challenges has been rising." Even  
unsuccessful challenges sometimes delay construction of educational  
utopias, "for the controversy itself can disrupt school operations and  
interfere with implementation of the program." Then there's the dreaded  
ripple effect: "When materials or programs are attacked in one school  
district, the controversy often affects other districts."  <p>
  
In a fit of candor, McCarthy advised her colleagues to drop their pretense  
of impartiality and give up trying to appease parents. "Instead of arguing  
that the challenged instructional programs are value-neutral or trying to  
sanitize the curriculum so that no groups are offended, policymakers and  
educators need to take a stand," exhorted McCarthy. She thus confirmed  
what many conservative parents have suspected all along: that educators  
are fighting an undeclared war against families with traditional values.  
We should thank Martha McCarthy for letting parents know what they're  
up against.  <p>
  
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit  
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free  
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free   
transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St.  
Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p>
