<head>
<title>Television's New Fall Lineup -- Duplantier</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">

<center>
<h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</h4>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
F.R. Duplantier <br>
October 6, 1995</i><br><hr>

<h2>Televisions New Fall Lineup</h2></center>

Does art imitate life, or does life imitate art? Television's new fall lineup may hold the answer.<p>

The question -- whether art imitates life, or vice versa -- can be applied 
fruitfully to television, if one assumes a loose interpretation of the word 
art, which, of course, is the interpretation in vogue. The "situations" in 
some television programs do reflect an existing reality, while others 
clearly serve as models for imitation. Most, however, fall somewhere in 
between mere re-creation and outright advocacy. The single-parent TV 
family, for instance may now reflect an unfortunate demographic trend, 
but it's been a television standby for years. Perhaps the phenomenon 
began as a matter of plot convenience, or as a cheap trick for winning 
instant sympathy for the main character. Whatever the case, on TV at 
least, the broken home has proven to be more enduring than the 
traditional American family as memorialized in Leave It to Beaver. Ozzie 
and Harriet, and The Dick Van Dyke shows. Nowadays, only minority 
families are allowed to remain intact on television.<p>

Which comes first, the broadcast broken home or the real-life broken 
home? It's hard to say. Nevertheless, the number of broken homes on TV 
is disproportionately high and constitutes a distortion of reality. Single-
parent TV families naturally lend themselves to grief mongering. What in 
public schools today goes by the name of "Death Education" has wormed 
its way into prime-time programming. Those single-parent TV families 
that have not resulted from divorce presuppose the death of one of the 
spouses. Such programs encourage the immature viewer to contemplate 
the prospect of his own parents' estrangement from each other, as well as 
the even grimmer possibility of their untimely deaths.<p>

Casual sexual practices are also more prevalent on the air than off. and 
gratuitous displays of flesh and simulated carnality are on the rise, 
especially in "dramatic" serials. Raunchiness and the rapidly changing 
multiple-plot format often go hand in hand, for they both pander to the 
demand for immediate gratification. The mature, loving relationship and 
the sophisticated, sustained plot require a keener insight into human 
nature and a greater attention span than are commonly possessed by 
people who respond to mental images with their sweat and salivary 
glands. With their incessant jumping from one swiftly developing plot to 
another. and the endless permutations of "relationships," the nighttime 
soaps are custom-made for the impatient hedonist.<p>

As with each new television season, there are one or two bright spots on 
the video horizon. Most of the new shows, of course, will fail to generate 
any significant interest among jaded television viewers, and some will set 
new standards for the stinker. A rare few will carve out audiences 
sufficient to perpetuate their existence. Still, we'd all be better off if the new fall lineup were completely disappointing. Then maybe we'd find the 
time, and the energy, to read a book, dine out with our spouses, play 
games with the kids, or visit the neighbors.<p>

<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free 
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. 
Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br>
<center>
