<head>
<title>Central Intelligence Agency -- Duplantier</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>

<h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</h4>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
F.R. Duplantier <br>
October 12, 1995</i><br><hr>

<h2>Central Intelligence Agency</h2></center>

The major media chastised the CIA for taking so long to ferret out Soviet 
mole Aldrich Ames. But the media itself may be partly to blame for 
undermining the Agency's ability to protect itself:<p>

"The announcement of the arrest of Aldrich Ames early last year. and the 
details of his horrific work as a Soviet mole inside the CIA for nine years, touched off a firestorm of attacks on the CIA itself," says James Tyson, president of the Council for the Defense of Freedom, and a former OSS officer. Tyson says the major media criticized the CIA for its 
"negligence" in allowing Ames's dirtv work to go undetected for so long, 
attributing that negligence to the reluctance of the agency's "Old Boy 
Network" to suspect one of its own. At least four major books have been 
rushed into print to add fuel to the fire.<p>

"What has not been recognized," Tvson charges, "is that the media and 
some of the book authors are themselves greatly responsible for the 
weakness in the CIA's counterintelligence operations. which allowed 
Ames to operate freely." According to Tyson. it was "the media vendetta 
on the CIA and its counterintelligence that led to ag,itation in Congress 
and successive presidential administrations. resulting in the firing of the 
counterintelligence head. James J. Angleton, and a virtual dismantling of 
the CIA's counterintelligence staff. This in turn caused the Agency to be 
vulnerable to the operations of a Sos iet mole like Aldrich Ames."<p>

Undermining the counterintelligence capability of the CIA was a major 
communist objective. says Tyson. "In the 1 960s and '70s, the Soviet 
Union under Khrushchev and his successors mounted a massive 
propaganda campaign against the CIA, much more effective than the 
clumsy efforts of the Stalin regime. The Soviets," Tyson reminds us, 
"regarded the CIA as a major threat. the eyes and ears of their main 
enemv. the United States. In the '70s, the campaign reached a climax with 
increasingly strident attacks by ultra-liberals." CIA critics jumping on the bashers bandwagon included "communist front groups like the National 
Lawers Guild and farleft Soviet sympathizers like the Institute for 
Policy Studies." <p>

Tyson recalls that President Gerald Ford and CIA Director William Colby 
made "many well-meaning but naive attempts to cooperate with reform 
efforts." Colby eventually fired counterintelligence chief Jarnes Angleton 
and many of his top aides. and was himself later fired by Ford. 
"Angleton's competence and reputed paranoia about moles is still a matter 
of disagreement among experts," concedes Tyson. "but there is no doubt 
that, after firing him.Colby and his successors went too far in virtually 
dismantling the counterintelligence capability."<p>

Under President Carter, hundreds of counterintelligence agents were let 
go. Eventually, the top echelon in the Agency began to emphasize 
technical means of acquiring intelligence. such as satellite photographs, 
in preference to traditional espionage. Tyson says "the main lesson of the 
Ames disaster is not the need to reform the CIA's 'Old Boy Network' and 
out-of-date procedures, but to restore its capacity for human 
intelligencegathering, especially in the counterintelligence area."<p>

<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. 
Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br>
