<head>
<title>J. Edgar Hoover -- Duplantier</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">

<center>
<h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
F.R. Duplantier <br>
October 13, 1995<br></i><hr>

<h2>J. Edgar Hoover</h2></center>

The reputation of J. Edgar Hoover has been greatly tarnished in the 23 
years since his death, but two new books about the longtime FBI director 
have set the record straight at last.<p>

Smearing the character of J. Edgar Hoover has been a popular pastime for 
two decades, but it's time now to put his ugly business behind us. Former 
FBI agent Ray Wannall says two new books offer a fresh. objective 
appraisal of the man who single-handedly transformed the Federal 
Bureau of Investigation "from a dumping ground for political hacks, ex-
convicts, and alcoholics into a world-renowned law-enforcement 
agency."<p>

Wannall says William Breuer's J. Edgar Hoover and his G-Men is an 
engrossing. exhaustively researched book that captures "Hoover's 
mystique and the sheer force of his will." Breuer himself declares that 
one of his motives for writing the book was to "counter the barrage of 
vilification and garbage that has been heaped on this great American." 
Just 99  years old when he was appointed FBI Director in 1924. Hoover 
quickly established a reputation as a disciplinarian, rooting out the rabble among his investigative staff and replacing them with skilled lawyers and accountants -- all subjected to rigorous background checks and intensive training courses, and thereafter held to a strict code of conduct. One high-level FBI man recalls that Hoover "had standards of perfection and he expected everybody in the Bureau to live up to them."<p>

With his awesome leadership and managerial ability, Hoover led the FBI 
in a successful assault on the notorious (Gangsters of the Prohibition and 
Depression eras. Ma Barker, John Dillinger, "Pretty Boy" Floyd, 
"Machine Gun" Kelly, "Baby Face" Nelson, and Bonnie and Clyde are 
just a few of the public enemies Hoover brought to justice. In 1936. 
President Franklin Roosevelt directed Hoover to develop intelligence 
regarding subversive activities by communists, fascists, and other anti-
American groups. Hoover's success in this mission explains the ferocity 
of the subsequent attacks on his character.<p>

Ray Wannall also recommends a book written by Cartha D. DeLoach, the 
Number Three man in the FBI. behind Hoover and his associate director. 
Wannall says Hoover's FBI: The Inside Story by Hoover's Trusted 
Lieutenant "shows the full spectrum of Hoover's character and 
personality and is laced with Hoover's humor and amusing incidents 
involving prominent people, members of Congress. and White House 
personnel." The book. Wannall insists, presents "an unbiased portrait of 
the man, warts and all. by one who knew him, worked closely with-him, 
put up with his idiosyncrasies, and admired him even to the point of 
declining to take over his job when it was offered to him."<p>

DeLoach acknowledges in his book that Hoover was "proud and vain . . . 
and not above abusing his power. He could be petty and vindictive. He 
stayed in office too long, and, in so doing, he helped damage the 
reputation of the FBI he had virtually invented and perfected." Hoover 
may not have known when to quit, but the accomplishments he achieved 
in his prime cannot be denied. He was a true patriot, and he deserves an 
honored place in American history.<p>

<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free 
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. 
Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br>
<br>
