<html><head>
<title>The U.N.'s Checkered Past -- Duplantier</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</h4>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
F.R. Duplantier<br>
 October 17, 1995 <br></i>
<hr>
<h2>The U.N.'s Checkered Past</h2></center>
<P>

 
Before we get caught up in all the hoopla surrounding the 50th  
anniversary of the United Nations, let's review the checkered past of this  
would-be world government. 
                                                          <P>
The United Nations was designed to serve the interests of the Soviet  
Union. The principal author of the UN Charter, and its first Secretary  
General, was Communist spy Alger Hiss, and the only nation allotted  
three votes, rather than one, was the Soviet Union. The second UN  
Secretary General, Trygve Lie (PRONOUNCED: LEE), revealed in his  
book, called In the Cause of Peace, that U.S. Secretary of State Edward  
Stettinius made a deal with Soviet Foreign Minister Molotov that the  
second most important position in the UN would always be held by a  
Communist. 
                                   <P>
From the beginning, the Soviet Union used the UN as a headquarters for  
espionage and terror. According to the 1956 Annual Report of the Senate  
Internal Security Subcommittee, "Accreditation to a diplomatic or  
semidiplomatic position frequently has been given to members of the  
Soviet secret police as a 'cover' for their real objectives in the United  
States.... Soviet agents have engaged, within the boundaries of the U.S.,  
in kidnapping and coercion of foreign nationals who are United States  
residents."                      <P>
 
The Soviet Union also used the UN as a platform in the heart of New  
York City from which to spread revolutionary and subversive  
propaganda. A UN delegate from Poland who defected to the United  
States testified that his Soviet masters considered the UN "one of the  
most important platforms for Soviet propaganda in the world." In 1952 a  
Senate investigation into the "Activities of United States Citizens  
Employed by the United Nations" produced voluminous evidence that  
"there is a Communist 'fifth column' operating within the UN  
Secretariat." 
                                                              <P>
The first war waged by the UN was the Korean War of 1950-53. Korea  
became a battlefield only because the Soviet Union was temporarily  
boycotting the UN and the Soviet delegate was not present to cast a veto  
the day the United States requested UN action. Thereafter, however, the  
Soviets used their position and influence in the UN to force a stalemate in  
Korea. The Soviets never made the mistake of boycotting again, and  
never again did the UN lend assistance to the victims of Communism --  
among them Albania, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, East Germany, Estonia,  
Hungary, Lithuania, Latvia, Poland, Rumania, and Tibet. 
                                                <P>
The UN did take immediate action in the Congo, however, speedily  
dispatching a "peace force" to wage war against the anti-communists of  
Katanga. UN troops killed women and children, attacked schools,  
hospitals, and churches, and used every means at their disposal to force  
the anti-communist Katangans into a Communist coalition government  
dominated by Soviet-trained agents. 
                                                         <P>
This is the history the United Nations will be celebrating next week --  
fifty years of smearing the reputation of the United States and  
undermining our interests, fifty years of providing a propaganda forum  
and an espionage base for the Soviet Union, fifty years of ignoring the  
victims of Communist aggression and actively helping to extend the  
reach of the evil empire.                   <P>
 
<p>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br>
