<html><head>
<title>Oppose The UN Convention on Discrimination Against Women -- Duplantier</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>
October 26, 1995 <br></i>
<hr>
<h2>Oppose The UN Convention on Discrimination Against Women</h2></center>
<P>

 
The United Nations Convention on Discrimination Against Women  
would upset the constitutional balance of power between our federal and  
state governments, undermine many of the rights possessed by American  
women, and subject our society to regulation by a committee of  
international inquisitors. 
                            <P>
The very first article of the UN Treaty on Women should have aroused  
the suspicions of every U.S. Senator. How could anyone sworn to uphold  
the U.S. Constitution fail to recognize the impropriety of ratifying a  
treaty that candidly promises to control "private organizations and even  
interpersonal relationships," and to reach into areas that are not regulated  
by the federal government? Neither magnifying glass nor fine-tooth comb  
was needed to examine this treaty; the threats it poses to our nation's  
sovereignty and the rights of American citizens are writ large! 
                       <P>
Article 2. for example, would invalidate laws that register males only for  
military service and assign males only to combat duty. Does any Senator  
believe that the majority of the American people favor the drafting of  
women and their assignment to the combat infantry? Article 2 would also  
require Congress to pass "appropriate corrective legislation" to regulate  
"membership in private clubs or organizations." Would this mean the  
sexual integration of women's colleges, of professional sports  
organizations, of Scout troops, of convents and monasteries? You bet it  
would! 
                               <P>
That's not the half of it. Make no mistake about it: what we're talking  
about here is the other half In the interest of eliminating alleged  
discrimination against the half of the population that is female,  
everything must be cut in half. Article 4 authorizes strict sexual quotas in  
employment, stipulating that special measures "aimed at accelerating de  
facto equality between men and women shall not be considered  
discrimination." Article 10 would require the "elimination of any  
stereotyped concept of the roles of men and women at all levels and in all  
forms of education, " and that means both public and private schools. 
                                       <P>
Article 11 would require Congress to legislate Comparable Worth, the  
feminist notion that government functionaries should establish wage  
scales based on their own subjective notions of "value." Never mind the  
influence of such market variables as the availability of labor, the demand  
for a given product or service, and the cost of living in a given area.  
Never mind that all the countries that rely on government-set wages have  
lower wages, and lower standards of living, than we Americans do.  
Article 11 would also require "the establishment and development of a  
network of child-care facilities," so that all women would be free to cast  
off the joys of motherhood and revel in the drudgery of wage labor.  
Article 16 would keep down the demand for such child care facilities by  
providing for abortion on demand. To make sure that all the preceding  
articles are adhered to, Article 17 would bring us under the supervision of  
a committee of 23 so-called experts elected from countries dominated by  
repressive regimes. 
 <p>                                         <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br>
