<html><head><title>Duplantier:  UNITED NATIONS REPATRIATES ASIAN REFUGEES</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>November 15, 1995<br></i><hr><h2>United Nations Repatriates Asian Refugees</h2></center><P>



       

[The United Nations High Commission on Refugees has long denied 
reports that it mistreats Asian refugees, forcibly returning many of them 
to the Communist countries from which they fled. But now former 
officials of the UN High Commission have come forward to confirm 
those reports.]
<p>
Officials of the United Nations High Cornrnission on Refugees and 
spokesmen from our own State Department persist in claiming that 
screening procedures for the Vietnamese and Laotian refugees detained 
in holding camps in Thailand. Hong Kong, Malaysia, and Indonesia are 
fair and orderly. They also maintain that the poor souls who have been 
repatriated have nothing to fear from the ruthless thugs who rule their 
homelands. These claims have now been challenged, however -- by 
former officials of the UN High Commission itself.
<p>
One such official is Simon Jeans, an Australian attorney who served as a 
legal consultant to the UN High Commission on Refugees in Indonesia 
in 1992. At a recent House of Representatives subcommittee hearing. 
Jeans testified to rampant corruption by the Indonesian officers in charge 
of the refugee camps. "Corruption in Indonesia was systematic," said 
Jeans. Bribes and sexual favors were the price paid for preferential 
treatment.
<p>
Another witness before the House subcommittee was Wa Vue. a leader of 
the Hmong tribal people of Laos. This tribe was an unwavering 
Arnerican ally during the Vietnam war, and its members were postwar 
victims of a violent campaign of genocide by the communist Lao 
government. More than l 00 000 Hmong have found sanctuary in the 
United States, but thousands more live in daily dread of repatriation as 
they languish in the holding camps in Thailand.
<p>
Wa Vue and his father, Vue Mai, were detained in one of those camps. 
Vue Mai was active in a resistance movement known as the United Front 
for the Liberation of Laos. Officials from the UN High Commission and 
the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok persuaded Vue Mai to give up this effort 
and return to Laos. In November 1992 a State Department 
representative, accompanied by Thai and UN officials. escorted Vue Mai 
to the border. He was to meet with Lao officials and arrange for the 
resettlement of a large number of Hmong refugees. In October 1993 he 
disappeared in Laos and has not been heard from since. On February 26, 
1995, the rest of the Vue clan -- except for Vue Mai's wife and his son, 
Wa Vue -- were rounded up and forcibly returned, presumably to suffer a 
similar fate.
<p>
"This tragic tale is further evidence that the United States should 
reexamine its role in refugee screening and treatment in Southeast Asia," 
argues James Tyson, president of the Council for the Defense of 
Freedom. "Contrary to State Department assertions, the House 
subcommittee hearing brought out further evidence that such screening 
is extremely unfair, corrupt, and often violent." Many of the refugees 
from tyrannical regimes in Southeast Asia were loyal allies of the U.S. 
during the Vietnam War, says Tyson. "We have a real obligation to see 
that they receive equitable hearings."

<p>                           <P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br><center><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body></html>
