<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  LEGALIZED GAMBLING DESTROYING COMMUNITIES</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>November 29, 1995<br></i><hr><h2>Legalized Gambling Destroying Communities</h2></center><P> 
 
[The social and economic havoc that legalized gambling is wreaking on  
communities throughout our country could have been avoided, if only  
Americans had learned the lessons of history.]  
  <p>
"On the whole, legalization of gambling in the United States has failed  
completely. Instead of eliminating abuses, it increased them . . .  
legalization attracted criminals." That's the conclusion of Virgil Peterson,  
onetime director of the Chicago Crime Commission. Mr. Peterson made  
those remarks in the 1950s, but they're even more appropriate today, now  
that state lotteries and gambling casinos have sprouted up all over the  
country.  
  <p>
"Commercialized vice and gambling have always been the principal  
props of the underworld," said Peterson, more than 40 years ago. "The  
intrinsic character of gambling naturally attracts the criminal element.  <p>
The kidnapper, the armed robber, the burglar, and the thief engage in  
their criminal enterprises for the purpose of obtaining money without  
working. Gambling establishments appeal to this type of individual."  
  <p>
In 1956 a New Orleans newspaper published a series of editorials  
reminding its readers of the many social ills that inevitably result when  
commercial gamblers are allowed to gain a foothold in a community.  
New Orleanians should have known better. After all, the city had had a  
long history of legal and illegal gambling and the dire consequences were  
a matter of public record. "Those who cannot remember the past are  
condemned to repeat it," said the philosopher George Santayana, and he  
might have added that there are always sharpies in the shadows waiting to  
cash in on our short memories.  
  <p>
The editorial writer for the New Orleans paper argued that "commercial  
gambling breeds official and political corruption. It is the incubator of the  
racketeer and the gangster." How do gambling interests gain a foothold?   <p>
What happened more than 40 years ago in Phenix City, Alabama typifies  
their methods: "The gamblers moved in, with the sanction of some  
officials. The bribe money looked good to them. They let more gamblers  
in. But the gambling profits looked even better. They moved in with the  
gamblers." Greed knows no limits, however. "Big, easy profits make big  
spenders. Big spenders seek bigger profits, and, eventually, some  
insurance that their profits will continue." Wherever the professional  
gambler operates, "he amasses a huge fortune which he eventually uses to  
influence government so as to insure not only his continued prosperity  
but an even greater one."  
  <p>
The newspaper warned that "the crime that gambling breeds is not  
confined to the professional gamblers. Infected also are hopeless  
gamblers. Like the dope addict, the gambling addict finds his fleeting  
thrills expensive. Money earned through lawful means rarely can support  
his pleasures. He turns to crime, to stickups, to burglary, to  
embezzlement, to white slavery, even to murder, for the fast buck that he  
needs to indulge himself."  
  <p>
Today's racketeers may have MBAs and designer suits, but they're still  
racketeers, and their activities are sucking the lifeblood out of our local  
economies and breeding vice. How much damage will they have to do  
before we send them packing?  
<p>                           <P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br><center><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body></html>
</DOC>
