<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  POLITICAL CHAOS AND THE DECAY OF LANGUAGE</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>December 7, 1995<br></i><hr><h2>Political Chaos and the Decay of Language</h2></center><P> 
[British writer George Orwell is best remembered for the novels 1984 and 
Animal Farm, two of the most prophetic satires about 20th Century 
socialism ever written. But Orwell was also a prolific journalist and 
essayist. A short piece he wrote entitled "Politics and the English 
Language" should be required reading for anyone who wants to explore 
the connection between degraded language and political tyranny.] 
 <p>
The quality of our language and the quality of our thought are 
inextricably linked. Our language "becomes ugly and inaccurate because 
our thoughts are foolish," said George Orwell, "but the slovenliness of 
our language makes it easier for us to have foolish thoughts." Orwell was 
convinced that we could improve the quality of our language and the 
quality of our thought if we would just pay more attention to what we say 
and write. "Modern English," he said, "is full of bad habits which spread 
by imitation and which can be avoided if one is willing to take the 
necessary trouble. If one gets rid of these habits, one can think more 
clearly, and to think more clearly is a necessary first step toward political 
regeneration." 
 <p>
Among the bad linguistic habits Orwell identified are worn-out 
metaphors, pretentious diction, and meaningless words. Many metaphors 
"have lost all evocative power and are merely used because they save 
people the trouble of inventing phrases for themselves." Who today can 
even recall what it originally meant to "toe the line" or "ride roughshod 
over"?  Pretentious diction, particularly the use of polysyllabic words of 
foreign derivation, is a nasty habit favored by "scientific, political and 
sociological writers" who are "haunted by the notion that Latin or Greek 
words are grander than Saxon ones." The worst habit of all is to use 
language, our tool of communication, in such a way as to communicate 
nothing.  "In certain kinds of writing, " said Orwell, "particularly in art 
criticism and literary criticism, it is normal to come across long passages 
which are almost completely lacking in meaning." 
 <p>
Orwell observed that "modern writing at its worst does not consist in 
picking out words for the sake of their meaning and inventing images in 
order to make the meaning clearer. It consists in gumming together long 
strips of words which have already been set in order by someone else. <p> 
"This allows us to avoid the difficult task of thinking.  If we get out of the 
habit of thinking, however, we become susceptible to all sorts of 
foolishness. 
 <p>
Political writing nowadays is invariably "bad writing," said Orwell, 
because it is used primarily for the "defense of the indefensible." 
Euphemism, evasion, and vagueness are its main characteristics. Every 
conscientious citizen must be in the habit of thinking, and pay close 
attention, if he is to avoid being victimized by the obfuscations of 
demagogues. Orwell encouraged all true patriots to "recognize that the 
present political chaos is connected with the decay of language."  He 
urged us to defend our liberties by defending our language. 
 <p>                           <P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br><center><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body></html>
