<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  ARISTOTLE ON DEMOCRACY</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>
December 8, 1995
<br></i><hr>
<h2>Aristotle on Democracy</h2></center><P> 

[The Greek philosopher Aristotle analyzed the benefits and 
disadvantages of various forms of government. His comments on the 
nature of democracies are especially valuable to Americans.]
<P>
Aristotle believed that communities are established when men are 
"drawn together by a common interest," each attaining "a share in good 
life." This good life is "the chief end, both for the community as a whole 
and for each of us individually." Aristotle argued that monarchies, 
aristocracies, and democracies can all be acceptable to the citizens of a 
country if their constitutions are just: "Those constitutions which 
consider the common interest are right constitutions," said Aristotle. 
"Those constitutions which consider only the personal interest of the 
rulers are all wrong constitutions, or perversions of the right forms."
<P>
Justice demands that a nation's rulers -- whatever their number -- be 
bound by law. Men have a right to expect impartiality when they sue for 
justice. For this they need "a neutral authority; and law is a neutral 
authority." The sovereignty of the law must supersede the sovereignty of 
the ruler. The law is a higher authority than the ruler because it proceeds 
from a higher authority. "He who commands that law should rule 
[commands] that God and reason alone should rule," said Aristotle: "he 
who commands that a man should rule adds the character of the beast."
<P>
Democracies inevitably decline when they cease to respect this higher 
authority and place the interests of any one group above the common 
good. In so doing, they ultimately destroy their middle classes. Without 
those middle classes, or "golden mean." democracies are left with 
"people who are ignorant how to rule and only know how to obey, as if 
they were so many slaves, and, on the other hand, people who are 
ignorant how to obey any sort of authority and only know how to rule as 
if they were masters of slaves." Clashes between the envious and the 
contemptuous will soon level such a state. "Nothing could be further 
removed from the spirit of friendship or the temper of a political 
community," warned Aristotle. "Community depends upon friendship."
<P>
The continued existence of a substantial middle class in America is vital 
to the preservation of our form of government. Every assault upon the 
middle class threatens to undermine the integrity of that government. 
The most obvious assault upon the middle class is our confiscatory 
income tax. The progressive income tax was one of Karl Marx's goals, 
and he supported it specifically to impoverish the middle class, thereby 
polarizing society and promoting class warfare. If we are to retain our 
freedom, we must protect this beleaguered middle class from further 
encroachment. Efforts to restore our constitutional government would be 
greatly facilitated by a swelling of the middle class. We are indebted to 
Aristotle for his exposition of the crucial role that the middle class plays 
in safeguarding freedom and a just society.
<p>                           <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br><center><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body></html>
