<title>Beltway, U.S.A.
 -Dec. 20, 1996
 - by Andy Ingram
</title>
<meta name="description" content="Beltway, U.S.A., A daily look at the Moral, Ethical and Financial issues facing America by Andrew Ingram">
<meta name="keywords" content="Beltway USA U.S.A. Moral Ethical Financial Andy Ingram Andrew 495 conservative Conservative editorial opinion Town Hall townhall TownHall">

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<blockquote><blockquote>
<center>
<img alt="Beltway, U.S.A." src="/townhall/columnists/ingram/beltwayusa.gif">
<br><i>A daily look at the Moral, Ethical and Financial issues facing America</i>
<p>


<h2>English Out, Ebonics In</h2> 
<i>December 20, 1996</i>
</center>
<p>
<br>
<p>

It has finally happened.  We have given up trying to educate our youth.  I don't see how we can expect to teach our children physics, or calculus if we can't be bothered to teach them proper English.
<p>
This week, the Oakland school board unanimously voted to recognize "black English" as a second language equal to that of Spanish or Chinese. "Ebonics," a term derived by combining the terms Ebony and Phonics, allows sentences with double negative such as "I'm not going back there no more." and with absences of the verb "to be" such as "she be at the store." Ebonics is heard on the streets and in many rap artist's songs.
<p>
In addition to this, the school district is likely to apply for federal money to pay for this bilingual education.  It's bad enough to recognize that sometimes youth create slang words like "awesome" or "cool", but to spend money encouraging it, is societal suicide.
<p>
Many blacks find this "give-up" attitude in education extremely patronizing. Steve Gooden, a black who attended the Republican convention in  San Diego said, "This cuts to the heart of the issue, --defining us as genetically deprived."  Many people worry that this might be an excuse to lower the education standards for the black community including Delain Eastin, the state education superintendent.
<p>
English is an incredibly complicated language, but it is necessary to make to effort to educate our youth, especially those from disadvantaged areas, in what the proper use of English is.  No one speaking in sentences with double and triple negatives is going to get chosen for a high paying career job. 
<p>
We have to expect more from our children, as they will only achieve what we ask of them.   We would not accept our children thinking two plus two equaled seven and we should not accept slang as proper speech.
<p>
As long as there a people on this earth, we are going to have different languages and dialects but we can hold to a single standard that can survive changes in the immediate culture.  It should not surprise us though.  Our society loves to soften rules.  Religious people of all faiths used to view their faith as the one true absolute and now you often hear people saying "I like that part of Christianity and that part of Buddhism or Judaism."
<p>
At a time when over fifty percent of high school seniors have tries an illicit drug such as marijuana, LSD, and cocaine,  and the global marketplace is putting increased emphasis on education, we should not be accepting street language as another national language.



<p>
God bless you in your efforts,<p>
<center>
<img alt="Andrew Ingram" src="/townhall/columnists/ingram/sig.gif">
<p>
<br>
<p>
<i>Material is copyrighted to Beltway, U.S.A. Reproduction or retransmission is prohibited without permission of Beltway,USA</i>
. Beltway USA Columnists can be contacted at <a href="mailto:beltwayusa@aol.com">beltwayusa@aol.com</a>.
