<head>
<title>Beltway, U.S.A.
 -Dec. 19, 1996
 - by Andy Ingram
</title>
<meta name="description" content="Beltway, U.S.A., A daily look at the Moral, Ethical and Finical issues facing America by Andrew Ingram">
<meta name="keywords" content="Beltway USA U.S.A. Moral Ethical Financial Andy Ingram Andrew 495 conservative Conservative editorial opinion Town Hall townhall TownHall">

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<blockquote><blockquote>
<center>
<img alt="Beltway, U.S.A." src="/townhall/columnists/ingram/beltwayusa.gif">
<br><i>A daily look at the Moral, Ethical and Financial issues facing America</i>
<p>


<h2>Christmas Spirit?</h2> 
<i>December 19, 1996</i>
</center>
<p>
<br>
<p>
Many people across the nation think that our country is in a moral crisis and from the type of the news stories each evening describing murders, rapes, and adultery, I can't argue. For the next couple of weeks, though the Christmas season will fill most Americans will feelings of joy and hope. Hopefully it will remind people of our true calling in life: to be servants of our LORD.  Don't count on it.<p>

Last night, as I sat down to watch the news, I came across a shining example of the shallowness of the Christmas spirit. NBC had their annual Christmas special attended by dozens of celebrities, elected officials, cabinet secretaries, and the President and the First Lady, many of which have exposed their contempt for religious conservatives. 

<p>

Hosted by those ridiculous aliens from NBC's <i>Third Rock from the Sun</i>, it was one of the most overt commercial exploitation's of Christ that I have seen.  It made me really think what people really consider the definition of the "Christmas Spirit" to be.  The most common phrase uttered during to show was "season of peace and joy". Granted peace and joy is great, but Christmas is not the celebration of our ourselves. It is a celebration of the birth of Christ, our Savior.
<p>
Now, don't misunderstand me. I am not calling into question anyone's faith, but I do question why so quickly after Christmas, people forget what most of their favorite Christmas carols are about; the birth of Christ.
<p>
Ever since people of faith began to participate in large numbers in the political system, they have been under attack by the liberal establishment.  I've grown tired of hearing the term "religious-far-right-extreme conservative" used to describe every normal American who bothers to vote and happens to lead a life of faith in GOD.
<p>
The true spirit of Christmas should not end on January 2nd, when all the celebrating is over.  We must carry it over into our daily lives. Hymns and carols about Christ don't have to disappear after Christmas. We need to continue to be charitable to those less fortunate. And we need to remember the greatest gift we've ever received; the Savior from GOD.
<p>
Santa can't hold a candle to that.
<p>
Christmas is the celebration of a new life, and yet shortly after Christmas, I am sure we will hear more anti-religious bigotry from the left.  It won't be long before the issue of protecting unborn children will be before Congress, and I hope that the people we invest our trust and democracy to, will think back to this Christmas and the shape our nation is in and do the right thing. Protect another beautiful life.
<p>
God bless you in your efforts,<p>
<center>
<img alt="Andrew Ingram" src="/townhall/columnists/ingram/sig.gif">
<p>
<br>
<p>
<i>Material is copyrighted to Beltway, U.S.A. Reproduction or retransmission is prohibited without permission of Beltway,USA</i>
. Beltway USA Columnists can be contacted at <a href="mailto:beltwayusa@aol.com">beltwayusa@aol.com</a>.<p>


