<html>
<head>
<title>Rockwell: Ending the Fed's Free Ride -- 04/09/96
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<i>
 April 9, 1996
</I>
<h2> Ending the Fed's Free Ride
</h2>
Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr.
<p>


Today's civics test: what Washington institution can make or  
break elections, bail out entire foreign governments, send the  
stock market to the stratosphere, or bankrupt whole industries,  
yet operates with less oversight than even the CIA?  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


One hint: the U.S. Constitution is useless as a cheat sheet  
(as it would be for any realistic civics exam these days.) The 
answer is the Federal Reserve, the most powerful yet least  
questioned any D.C. bureaucracy. Will that soon change?  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


At issue is a new report on the Fed, released by Government  
Accounting Office just as Alan Greenspan seeks Senate  
confirmation for his third term. The report pulled back the  
curtain, just a smidgen, on the Fed's notorious secrecy. Now some  
Senators and pressure groups are gearing up to give the Fed the  
what-for.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


Among other revelations in the report is the Fed's  
heretofore secret "contingency fund"--that is, slush  
fund--totaling $3.7 billion. It comes from money that the Fed has  
skimmed off the revenues gained from its open-market operations.  
Everyone thought revenues were turned over to the Treasury.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


And that's far from the only slush sluicing through the  
halls of the Fed's marble temple on Constitution Ave. From 1988  
to 1994, the Fed's spending on its own lifestyle grew at twice  
the rate of inflation.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


Mr. Greenspan protests the suggestion that the Fed is  
wasting taxpayer dollars. He's technically right. The Fed doesn't  
need our taxes any more than a counterfeiter needs to hold up the  
local gas station. The central bank using fancy finance to  
effectively print all the money it needs.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


In its never-ending quest to expand money and credit, the  
Fed can lower the rate it charges member banks for loans, it can  
manipulate reserve requirements, or, most notoriously, it can buy  
Treasury securities on the open market.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


It's this last action that proves so profitable. The Fed  
purchases Treasury securities--either directly or through  
favorite brokerage houses--and holds this debt as an asset.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


Working through its branches and member banks, it pyramids  
loans on top of these securities. The creditworthiness of the  
U.S. government--whose balance sheet would otherwise suggest  
Chapter 7--is entirely due to this power of the Fed.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


The real oddity--and this is where the power to counterfeit  
comes in--is where the Fed gets the money to purchase these debt  
securities. It creates it out of thin air, a magic trick made  
easier as the current paper money system replaced the restrictive gold 
standard.   
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


If anyone tries this at home, the Justice Department lands  
him in the pokey. When third-world countries are rumored to be  
circulating phony dollars, the military threatens to bomb them.  
To stop counterfeiting is why the Treasury says it redesigned the  
$100 bill. It could also be cracking down on the competition.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


Now to the Fed's just-discovered $3.7 billion slush fund. It  
represents a small slice of the profits the Fed derives from  
exacting interest payments on the debt it holds. And who pays  
that interest? You and me, in the form of tax dollars. At the end  
of the year, the Fed gives some back and keeps the rest.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


The original argument for creating the Fed is that it would  
eliminate banking crises that cause bank depositors to lose their  
money. Well, after 1913, the recessions increased in frequency,  
the government became vastly bigger, and the dollar lost about 97  
percent of its value. In one way or another, depositors have lost  
more money than ever.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


The Fed's fingerprints are all over these trends. Every new  
dollar created by the Fed's operations (all else being equal)  
waters down the value of the existing dollars circulating in the  
economy. And an ever-cheaper dollar redistributes money from  
savers to debtors, and from the tax-paying middle class to the  
banks and government contractors that spend the fresh money  
before prices rise.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


We hear that inflation is low, but look at the long-term  
trends. The dollar has lost three quarters of its value since  
Richard Nixon eliminated the last vestiges of the gold standard 
in 1971. Even at the present rate of inflation--and who believes  
that will last?--overall prices will have doubled when today's  
newborns enter the workforce.   
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


If we want to know why living standards are falling, the  
curtain needs to be pulled back even more. If we want to stop the  
fall, we need a truly redesigned money: a Fed-proof gold dollar.  
<p><P>
<i>
Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr., is president of the Ludwig von Mises 
Institute in Auburn, Alabama.<i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br><center>
