</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Rockwell: Oil in the Crossfire -- 4/30/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<i>
 APRIL 30, 1996
</i>

<h2>
Oil in the Crossfire
</h2>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/rockwell.html">
 Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr.
</a>

<P>


Now that National Hate AT&T Month is over, it's time to  
despise the oil companies. Call them any name you want: gougers,  
extortionists, or greed merchants. Make them the national enemy.  
It's a human rights violation to raise a price.  
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The occasion of the newest anti-capitalist hysteria is a  
one-year, 10% increase in gasoline prices at the pump. Never mind  
the underlying economic causes. Secretary of Energy Hazel O'Leary  
is investigating the oil industry to discover who's getting rich  
at the driver's expense.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Not to be left out, Connecticut's two Democratic  
Senators--Chris Dodd and Joe Lieberman--are demanding that  
Attorney General Janet Reno knock the heads of oil companies with  
a stump. Heaven knows she can do it, even without resorting to  
tanks and CS gas. Anti-trust law can be bent to make any price  
pattern appear illegal.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

For his part, President Clinton has decided to deal with the  
national emergency by dumping 12 million barrels onto the market  
from the Strategic Petroleum Reserve.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

All this reveals profound ignorance. Prices respond  
immediately to information about future demand and supply. If a  
credible announcement of a government oil sale didn't reduce the  
price, selling the oil won't do it either.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Recall that this administration complains about foreigners  
dumping their goods on American markets at below cost. However, 
when it's our own government doing the dumping, it's not a  
vicious practice, but a responsible economic policy.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The market specializes in allocating supplies over time via  
the price system. When supply is low and demand is high, prices  
rise to induce new drilling and distribution. In light of higher 
gasoline prices, consumers are already changing some summer  
travel plans, another market response.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The market's price system works so well it doesn't need  
management at all. We don't have a strategic shoe or chicken  
reserve, yet, somehow, we walk and eat. But it's not free-market  
logic that's driving Mr. Clinton's blue light special. He's  
looking to profit politically--we might even call it vote  
gouging--at the expense of private industry.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

A far better response--if highly atypical given their sorry  
record this year--comes from Republicans who are demanding a  
repeal of Mr. Clinton's 4.3 cent gas tax increase.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Democrats say the savings from a tax cut won't be "passed  
on" to the consumer. These are the same people who said a tax  
increase would be "passed on" two years ago. Not only that, they  
hoped it would be. In those days, you see, liberals agitated for  
higher gasoline prices as a way of inducing consumers to less, drive 
less, and "pollute" less.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Liberals love oil price increases, especially when they're  
caused by taxes. It's the best of both worlds: people have less  
fun and government gets to siphon off new revenue.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The last time the nation went bonkers over gas prices was  
during the Gulf War. The U.S. government jeopardized imports from  
the entire Arab world, and President Bush (A.B. economics, Yale  
University) was amazed and alarmed to see prices go up. Like Mr.  
Clinton now, he attempted to jawbone companies into cutting  
prices. Corporate executives feared for their bottom lines.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

There is always--as hard as government officials find this  
to accept--a purpose behind market-driven changes in price. If a  
good is more scarce, its price will rise so that people can know  
to use less of it. If it is more plentiful, its price will fall 
so consumers can know to live it up. Tampering with the system  
imposes unpredictable distortions.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

In a country built by free enterprise, there is still mass  
ignorance on what accounts for a price increase in an industry.  
It's not greed, gouging, or illicit gas guzzling. It's either an  
increase in demand, a decrease in supply, or a response to money  
creation by the Fed. No use looking anywhere else.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Just how badly do we want prices to fall? The best and  
surest way is to have free trade in oil. And, yes, that includes  
with Iraq, a country whose people have suffered immeasurably from  
the U.S.'s cruel and unusual sanctions.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

To end the war on the market before it escalates further, we  
need an end to embargoes, taxes, regulations, and inflation, all  
of which impede the right of Americans to determine their own  
strategic petroleum reserves. 
<P> 

<I> 
Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr., is president of the Ludwig von Mises  
Institute in Auburn, Alabama.<I>
<br>
<P><P>
</blockquote></blockquote>

<P> <br>
<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center>
<P>
