The Long Hot Summer Ahead   
 Thomas A. Schatz 
 Citizens Against Government Waste
 May 18, 1995 
 

 Outsiders usually aren't surprised -- and often think it appropriate  
-- when they learn that much of Washington was built on a swamp.  
While that fact only partially accounts for the hot gases that tend to 
swirl here, this summer promises to be stickier than most, with 
rhetorical fireworks flying that could dwarf the pyrotechnics on the 
4th of July.    

 Freon will be in short supply as the battle of the budget burns 
through the summer and into September.  The deficit hawks, promising a 
balanced budget by 2002, will square off against the special interests 
and sentinels of the status quo, who, as one Republican leader has 
said, have nothing to offer but fear itself.  At stake are the hearts 
and minds of everyday Americans and the political high ground as we 
move into an election year.   

 While every battle seems decisive from the perspective of the 
interlocked combatants, this time it's no exaggeration.  The outcome 
will determine whether future Americans are born debt-free, whether 
the growth of government can be reversed, whether the will of average 
taxpayers can prevail over the more focused energies of special 
interests, and whether Americans are still capable of sacrificing in 
the short term to safeguard the future.   

 The balanced budget proposals recently put forward -- reductions in 
spending of $1.4 trillion in the House and $961 billion in the Senate 
over seven years -- provide a game plan only, establishing broad 
budgetary parameters.  The specific cuts and final shape of the 
package will be hashed out during the summer.  Which components live 
or die will be determined in part by the war of words, by the ebb and 
flow of public opinion.     

 Even if every cut or reduction in growth being proposed survives, 
government spending will still grow from $1.53 trillion this year to 
$1.8 trillion in 2002.  Social Security spending, the "third rail" of 
American politics, is off the table.  Medicare (which will be bankrupt 
by 2002 without reform) will grow as well, but at a more manageable 
rate than 10 percent a year, its current pace.  At least one and 
perhaps as many as three federal departments could be eliminated 
altogether.  Hundreds of anachronistic agencies and programs will fall 
by the wayside.  These, in short, are some of the most dramatic 
changes in the size and scope of government since the heady days of 
the Great Society.  Only this time, contraction is the goal, rather 
than expansion.   

 What avenues will be taken to arrive at a smaller, more affordable 
government?  The first is privatization -- as first proposed by the 
Grace Commission more than a decade ago.  As the late J. Peter Grace 
recognized, there are many public entities that could stand alone as 
private, profit-making ventures.  Capitol Hill budget cutters are 
looking to privatize the Federal Aviation Administration, the Naval 
and Strategic Petroleum Reserves, and the National Helium Reserves.  
Also likely to be sold off are the nation's five Power Marketing 
Administrations, which sell power generated by federally-built 
hydroelectric facilities.  To this list, Citizens Against Government 
Waste would add the Tennessee Valley Authority, the National Weather 
Service, the space shuttle program, and the military commissary 
system.   

 Next is consolidation --  putting the government's self-duplicating 
and redundant functions under a single roof and reversing the 
politically-driven proliferation of cabinet-level agencies.  Should we 
do away with the Department of Energy, created in response to the 
energy crisis of the 1970's, its responsibility for nuclear weapons 
labs and facilities could easily be subsumed by the Department of 
Defense.  The Federal Highway Administration and the National Highway 
Safety Administration should be merged.  The military's four, separate 
health-care bureaucracies should be placed under single management.  
And there's much more consolidation that could be done.   

 When all else fails, there's always termination.  It's been said that 
there's nothing in the world more permanent than a temporary federal 
program.  The Appalachian Regional Commission (ARC) is a prime 
example.  Thirty years after being launched as a component of Lyndon 
Johnson's Great Society, the ARC serves today as little more than a 
pork-barrel for opportunistic politicians.  Three-quarters of a 
million dollars in ARC "anti-poverty" funds will be spent this year 
helping to build a practice facility for the NFL Carolina Panthers at 
a private college in Spartanburg, South Carolina, one of the most 
affluent counties in that state.  The Economic Development 
Administration, another anachronistic agency that should be 
terminated, has chipped in $500,000 more for the stadium.  The 
Interstate Commerce Commission, the bureaucracy that wouldn't die and 
occupies itself today publishing pamphlets about how to start a small 
railroad, also begs for a wooden stake through the heart.  There are 
many others that need to be added to the Endangered Bureaucracies 
List.   

 Another concept gaining popularity in Washington is "devolution," 
which is short-hand for returning power, money, and responsibility for 
administering certain programs back to the states.  The states, each 
working as individual laboratories, or incubators for innovation, will 
manage these programs more efficiently.  If all goes according to 
plan, Medicaid will be delivered to the states as a block grant, 
letting them dispense it as they see fit, as will food stamps.  Other 
welfare reform measures will also be downloaded to the state level.   

 Finally, even if the size of the federal government is reduced, much 
more can be done to make it run more like a business.  While not very 
"sexy," financial management reform is essential if we want the most 
efficient government for the money.  Unless there is full 
implementation of the Chief Financial Officers Act, and the 
bureaucracy is compelled to deliver timely, trustworthy financial 
reports, the ship of state sails in a fog and our leaders have no way 
to know which reforms are working and which aren't.   

 The road to a balanced budget won't be without its potholes: the 
whole effort may succumb to politics as usual and break down before it 
even gets going.  To succeed, many sacred cows will have to be put out 
to pasture.  Many old ways of thinking about government will have to 
be discarded.  We'll have to forge ahead even when the Chicken Littles 
and special interests say that the sky is falling.  After decades of 
saying "Yes," Washington's political class will have to bring itself 
to say "No."  In turn, voters will have to reward those who have the 
courage to say "No," holding up fiscal prudence rather than 
piggishness as a virtue, and learn to stop turning to the federal 
government for the solution to every imaginable problem.  An America 
increasingly fractured into adversarial special interests, each 
fighting for a piece of the pie, will have to find a way to coalesce 
around a new set of affordable national priorities.   

 In short, the era of governmental limits and fiscal responsibility 
won't be born without a long, painful, and noisy labor.   

  
  
To join CAGW and receive Government WasteWatch, the quarterly 
newsletter of Citizens Against Government Waste, please fill out this 
coupon and mail it with your tax-deductible contribution. 
 
