<html>
<title>
<Press Release: Welfare Reform and Illegitimacy</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>
News Release</h2>
<hr>
<i><b><a href="/heritage/">The Heritage Foundation</a></b><br>
214 Massachusetts Avenue, NE<br>
Washington, D.C. 20002<br>
(202) 546-4400</i>
<hr>
<h3>
<b>SENATE WELFARE REFORM BILL<br> 
FORGETS ILLEGITIMACY, ANALYSTS SAY<br></b></b>   
<p></h3><br>
</center><b>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
<p>
WASHINGTON, AUG. 29, 1995 --</b> The main welfare-reform bill the Senate will consider when Congress returns from recess all but ignores the most important reform issue -- illegitimacy -- according to a <a href="/heritage/library/categories/healthwel/cbrief18.html">study released today</a> by The Heritage Foundation.
<p>
The bill proposed by the Senate's Republican leadership contains only one of eight anti-illegitimacy provisions that are part of a bill sponsored by Sens. Lauch Faircloth, R-N.C., Phil Gramm, R-Texas, and John Ashcroft, R-Mo., according to <a href="http://www.townhall.com/heritage/staff/rector.htm">Robert Rector</a>,  Heritage senior policy analyst for welfare and family issues.
<p>
"For weeks liberal Republicans have fought behind the scenes to prevent other lawmakers from even mentioning the harmful effects of illegitimacy. Now the Senate leadership bill finally mentions those harmful effects on society, but it does not take steps to curb them," Rector says. He believes the Senate leadership should adopt all the Faircloth-Gramm-Ashcroft provisions. These include: 
<p><ul>
<LI>Requiring states to set voluntary 10-year goals for lower levels of illegitimacy and to draw up plans for reducing out-of-wedlock births.
<p>
<li>A federal bonus to states that are successful in reducing illegitimacy -- providing that abortion rates have not also increased.
<p>
<LI>Setting aside funds for abstinence education.
<p>
<LI>Providing a tax credit up to $500 for married couples with children with earned income between $8,000 and $26,000 where at least one spouse works.
<p>
<LI>Requiring mothers to establish paternity for children born after January 1996 in order to obtain future Aid to Families with Dependent Children (AFDC) benefits.
<p>
<LI>Stop providing federal cash benefits to girls under 18 years old who have children out of wedlock.
<p>
<LI>Stop providing additional federal aid to women who have more children while enrolled in AFDC. States would be able to use their own funding if they choose.
<p>
</ul>
In a related study, two former policy analysts in the Bush administration's Office of Population Affairs at the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services agree that abstinence training should be part of the welfare-reform package.
<p>
According to <a href="/heritage/library/categories/healthwel/bg1051.html">Joseph J. Piccione and Robert A. Scholle</a>, The Preventing Sexual Involvement (PSI) abstinence program conducted by Emory University faculty members is a perfect example of what the government can do to prevent illegitimacy.
<p>
A scientific study of PSI showed adolescents who went through the program were significantly less likely to initiate sexual activity than similar adolescents in a control group. In fact, non-program eighth-grade students were five times more likely to begin sexual activity during the school year than program students.
<p>
Piccione and Scholle recommend policy-makers:
<p><ul>
<li>Make abstinence counseling a part of comprehensive family planning.
<p>
<li>Give abstinence programs the same funding status as state and federally funded contraception programs.
<p>
<li>Promote adoption counseling where pregnancy has already occurred.
</ul>
<p>
"Abstinence programs must be part of a whole, unambiguous cultural message that promotes responsibility in all facets of life, including the sexual. Abstinence is the hallmark of responsibility. This message must be directed at both sexes and at all ages," they say.
<p>
Note: Joseph J. Piccione can be reached at (309) 655-2858 and Robert Scholle at (412) 422-9214.
<BR><HR WIDTH="30%"><BR><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER></body>
</html>


