<html>
<head>
<title>Rocky Mountain News -- PFF</title>
</head>
<center>
<img width=468 height=32 src="multi/gif/pff-header.gif"></center>
<p>
<p>
<center>
<h1>Rocky Mountains News</h1>
Denver -- August 20, 1995
<p>
<h2>"Aspen summit to explore cyberspace"</h2>
By Price Colman
<p>
<b>Conference designed to draft manifesto on sole technology will play in future society</b>
</center>
<p>
On the surface, the Ritz-Carlton in Aspen and Independence Hall in Philadelphia have little in common.  That could change if organizers of what's billed as "Aspen Summit:  Cyberspace and the American Dream II" see their vision become reality.  
<p> 
The Progress and Freedom Foundation, a Washington, D.C, - based think tank that is hosting the conference, has attracted a collection of America's brainest visionaries to Aspen with a plan in mind.  It hopes to draft a manifesto that will guide American society as it begins to probe the frontiers of cyberspace.  
<p>
"What we're trying to do is bring together those who see the potential of technology to work through what the future is going to be like,"  said Richard F. O'Donnell, spokesman for the foundation.  "We want to chart a path to show change can be good if we're smart.  If we think through where we're going, we can end up at better place than where we are today."
<p>
It's an ambitious mission, and the Progress and Freedom Foundation has lined up a panel of participants with intellectual clout.  
<p>
The participants inclued John Perry Barlow of the Electronic Frontier Foundation, Steward Brand of The Well and Whole Earth Catalog fame, Phill Burgess of the Center for the New West, Esther Dyson of EDventure Holdings, television and telecommunications visionary George Gilder, Microsoft genius Nathan Myhrvold, Bell Labs genius Arno Penzias and author and futurist Alvin Toffler.  
<p>
Sponsors of the summit include the Denver-based <a href="http://www.commerce.com/cnw/">Center for the New West</a>, a think tank financed primarily by U.S. West, Microsoft, the Reason Foundation, Intel, AT&T and BellSouth.
<p>
Participation in the summit won't be limited to big companies or famed Ph.Ds.  Anyone with a properly, equipped personal computer, or access to one, will be able to express views at this meeting of the minds aimed at drafting the operating principles of a new democratic digitocracy.
<p>
The Progress & Freedom Foundation has established a World Wide Web site --- <a href="http://aspen.pff.org">http://aspen.pff.org</a> -- permitting online participation in the four topics that will be featured at the summit.  The topics are the nature of property and freedom, the essence of community, the way of the marketplace and the role of government.
<p>
"The proceedings are going to be posted live real-time on the Net," said O'Donnell.  "People in cyberspace will be able to post comments about what's happening."
<p>
The Web site is operational now and accepting comments.
<p>
The Progress and Freedom Foundation may be best known for its sponsorship of the weekly cable television show Progress Report, co-hosted by House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., and for sponsoring the college course "Renewing American Civilization" that Gingrich taught.
<p>
But there's no partisan political agenda for the conference, O'Donnell emphasized.  
<p>
"We don't believe politically the left-right debate exists anymore," O'Donnell said.  "We think that debate is obsolete.  Americans no longer believe government has the answers.   We're trying to find a new paradigm.  We're kind of all over the map, just because we're trying to abandon the left-right debate."
<p>
As for the issue of why host such a conference in Aspen, O'Donnell offered a simple explanation.  "We wanted to do two things:  Get people away from daily routines to come and think," he said.  "The other thing is, Aspen's a great place to be in August."
<p>
<center>
<a href="/pff/><img alt="PFF Home Page" border=0 width=234 height=32 src="multi/gif/pff-footer-home.gif"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
