<html>
<title>Press Release: Abolish DOT, Return to States</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center><h2>News Release
</h2>
<hr>
<i><b><a href="http://www.townhall.com/heritage/">The Heritage Foundation</a></b><br>
214 Massachusetts Avenue, NE<br>
Washington, DC 20002 <br>
(202)546-4400</i>
<hr>
<h3><b>DOT DUTIES CAN BE HANDLED BY<br>
 STATES, BUSINESSES, ANALYSTS SAY<br></h3></b>
<p><br>
</center><b>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
<p>
WASHINGTON, AUGUST 16, 1995  --</b> Congress should abolish the<a href="http://www.dot.gov/"> Department of Transportation (DOT) </a>and return its functions -- including the federal highway program, Amtrak, Federal Transit Administration (FTA), and Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) -- to state and local governments or privatize them, according to a Heritage Foundation study released today.
<p>
"Federal involvement in transportation on land, sea and air has become costly, bureaucratic and inflexible, operating in a fashion that preserves privileges of businesses, civil servants, congressional committees and unions that benefit financially from the status quo," say Dr. Ronald Utt, a Heritage visiting fellow, and Wendell Cox, director of state policy and legislation for the American Legislative Exchange Council, authors of the study.
<p>
As an example, Utt and Cox cite DOT's highway program, which "Congress originally intended to be a federally assisted state program to which more and more federal mandates and money have been added, making it a state-assisted federal program." As a result, "a $30 billion program with a 15-year projected time for completion has incurred costs of more than $300 billion and is now 30 years behind schedule."
<p>
Closing DOT and decentralizing or privatizing its mostly commercial functions would build upon "fundamental transportation reforms that began with President Carter and carried over into the early Reagan administration" but stalled under George Bush and Bill Clinton, say Utt, former Reagan administration "privatization czar," and Cox.
<p>
The analysts recommend that the $20 billion Highway Trust Fund -- now used to pay for highway construction, urban mass transit subsidies, advanced transportation systems research and numerous other activities -- be abolished, and revenues from the 18.5 cents-per-gallon federal fuel tax that finance the fund become a block grant. Under such a scheme, each state would be free to distribute the funds among a variety of transportation purposes that best suit its needs, according to Utt and Cox.
<p>
Also, a new Interstate Transportation Safety Office would assume safety regulation duties now managed separately by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA), FAA and FTA.
<p>
 Utt and Cox recommend that Amtrak be terminated and its assets transferred to a new eight-state "Northeast Corridor Compact," which would seek creative ways to continue rail passenger service in the region. "Popular long-haul passenger routes should be privatized separately to take advantage of their tourism potential," say Utt and Cox.
<p>
The FAA would be split into three parts. "The air-traffic control system should be reorganized as an independent government corporation funded by user fees and ultimately privatized," the analysts say. Airport improvement would be restored to state and local governments along with the taxes and fees to fund the program.
<p>
Highway construction and maintenance would become state duties, while costly and burdensome federal labor and environmental mandates on construction projects receiving federal funds would end under the Heritage plan. A new federal highway cooperation office would be established to "bring together state officials to deal with issues of coordination among the states where needed."
<p>
Also, authority over the U.S. Coast Guard would be shifted to the Justice Department, while the Maritime Administration, with its $700 million-worth of Depression-era federal shipping subsidies, would be terminated.
<p>
Taken together in a DOT-closure measure, transportation deregulation would be to the "considerable benefit of America's consumers, workers and businesses," say Utt and Cox.
</body>
</html>
						

</DOC>
