http://www.conservative.org:80/heritage/news/trade.html 204.71.237.88 19970209104836 text/html 4250
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 10:49:22 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 20-Oct-95 14:32:17 GMT
Content-length: 4067
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<title>Press Release: </title><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<h2><center>News Release</h2>
<hr>
<i><b><a href="http://www.townhall.com/heritage/">The Heritage Foundation</a></b><br>
214 Massachusetts Avenue, NE<br>
Washington, D.C. 20002<br>
(202) 546-4400</i>
<hr>

<h3><b>ABOLISH COMMERCE,<br>
 DON'T CREATE NEW TRADE DEPARTMENT, ANALYST SAYS</h3></b><p>
<br>
</center><b>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
<p>
WASHINGTON, AUGUST 14, 1995 --</b> Congress should move forward with plans to abolish the U.S. Department of Commerce, but it should resist the temptation to create another Cabinet-level agency to handle international trade, a Heritage Foundation analyst said today. He called proposals to eliminate Commerce, while adding a new Department of International Trade, "a shell game."
<p>
Instead of playing this game, Commerce's legitimate duties in the trade area should be transferred to the Treasury Department, says economist <a href="http://www.townhall.com/heritage/staff/cobb.htm"> Joe Cobb.</a>
<p>
"The Commerce Department has 20 undersecretary and assistant secretary offices, six directors and administrators, and 263 political appointees, and shares four budgetary functions with eight other Cabinet or sub-Cabinet departments," Cobb says. "Commerce cannot be reinvented. The department should be abolished. Its obsolete and outmoded programs should be terminated. Its duplicative programs should be transferred to other departments. And its commercial activities should be privatized or closed," he says.
<p>
Creating a new Department of International Trade, which would include the office of the United States Trade Representative (USTR), as has been suggested by Rep. John Mica, R-Fla., and others, not only would be contrary to the goal of reducing government, but could harm U.S. trade interests, Cobb says. "It would diminish the USTR's effectiveness as a tough negotiator that speaks directly for the president in dealing with foreign governments," Cobb says. 
<p>
Transferring Commerce's trade programs to the <a href="http://www.ustreas.gov/treasury/homepage.html">Treasury Department</a>, Cobb says, would put them under "the government's principal officer for international economic policy," the Secretary of the Treasury.
<p>
On shutting down the Commerce Department itself, Cobb recommends that the department's inspector general be used to perform "the core of the transition work," that would either abolish outright, transfer to other agencies or privatize all of Commerce's more than 100 programs. Those programs create, according to the General Accounting Office, "a complex web of divided authorities" that shares "missions with at least 71 [other] federal departments, agencies and offices." 
<p>
Indeed, most of Commerce's activities, he says, "have little or nothing to do with its purported mission, which is encouraging the nation's international trade."
<p>
Among Cobb's detailed recommendations for abolishing Commerce:
<ul>
<li>Close the Economic Development Administration, U.S. and Foreign Commercial Service, Minority Business Development Agency, Travel and Tourism Administration, Office of Technology Policy, National Institute of Standards and Technology, and National Telecommunications and Information Administration;
<p>
<li>Transfer to other government offices the International Trade Administration, Bureau of Export Administration, and National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration;
<p>
<li>Privatize the National Technical Information Service and Patent and Trademark Office; and 
<p>
<li>Consolidate as a new, independent agency a combination of the Bureau of Census, the Economics and Statistics Administration and other federal statistical agencies.
</ul>	
<p>
"A Cabinet department reporting directly to the president of the United States ought to have a clearly defined mission and not continue year after year to function simply as an organization chart, tying together a loose collection of agencies," Cobb says. 
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
