</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title> Washington Leaders Join On-Line Cyberspace Summit  -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<p>
<Font Size="-1">
News Release<br>
August 14, 1995<br>
Contact: Rick O'Donnell -- 202-484-2312
</font>
<p>
<center>
<h2> Washington Leaders in On-Line Cyberspace Summit  </h2>
</center>
<p>

<b> Senate Minority Leader Thomas Daschle </B> (D-N.D.) and GOP presidential candidates <b>
Senator Richard Lugar </b> (R-Ind.) and <b> Lamar Alexander </b> are among those joining in an on-line discussion on the Internet in the run-up to this weekend's Aspen Summit '95.
<p>
 Both the Internet forum and the Summit itself are examining the nature of the Big Change happening in America as information technology transforms notions of property, freedom and community,along with the workings of the marketplace and the government.  Four on-line discussion groups at the Aspen Summit '95 Homepage (http://aspen.pff.org) are underway, with both leaders and citizens engaging in debate.
<p>
"We're bringing the leadership of Cyberspace together to develop a set of principles to guide us toward a better future in the Knowledge Age.  The on-line forums allow citizens to engage in a discourse withtheir leadership about where America is headed," said <b>Jeffrey A. Eisenach </b>, president of the Progress & Freedom Foundation, which is hosting the Aspen Summit '95.
<p>
Other leaders who have posted comments on the Homepage include <b> Representative Chris Cox</b> (R-Calif), who is active in the issue of freedom of speech on the Internet;  <b> Malcolm S. Forbes, Jr.</b>, the publisher who may seek the GOP presidential nomination, and <b> Senator Larry Pressler</b>, chariman of the Senate Commerce Committee.
<p>
On August 21 and 22, hundreds of people will gather in Aspen, Colo. for the Aspen Summit '95, which will continue the discussion begun on the Summit Homepage.  During the two days of the conference, live posting will occur on the Homepage, and comments left by those logging on will become part of the conference discussion.
<p>
"The Summit is about describing a path that will get us from here to there -- to life after the Big Change.  We need to think abouthow to get through this transformation of American life, and to our future," said 
<b> Michael Vlahos</b>, senior fellow at the Foundation who will be conference moderator.
<p>
The Progress & Freedom Foundation is a non-partisan research and educational organization dedicated to creating a positive vision of the future founded in the historic principles of the American idea.
<p>
