<html>
<head>
<title>Press Release -- Civil Rights</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">

<center>
<h2>News Release</h2>
<hr>
<i><b><a href="http://www.heritage.org">The Heritage Foundation</a></b><br>
214 Massachusetts Avenue, NE<br>
Washington, D.C. 20002<br>
(202) 546-4400</i>
<hr>
<h3><b>1964 CIVIL RIGHTS ACT SOLVES AFFIRMATIVE ACTION PROBLEMS, ANALYST SAYS</b></h3>
Congress Never Sanctioned "Affirmative Discrimination"<br>
<p> 	
</center>
<b>For Immediate Release<br>
Contact: Heritage Public Relations<br>
<p>
	WASHINGTON, AUGUST 7, 1995</b> -- If Congress wants to assure all Americans  equal treatment under the law on the job, all it has to do is enforce the original intent of Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, which "clearly forbids employment discrimination against either sex and against any racial or ethnic group,"  according to a former legal counsel for President Bush.<p>
	As part of this effort, lawmakers should forbid federal courts and regulatory agencies from imposing or encouraging race or sex-based "affirmative action" quotas or preferences, which are "alien to the fundamental principles of Title VII," says Nelson Lund, an associate professor at George Mason University School of Law writing in a <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/cbrief17.html"> Heritage Foundation special report</a> to Congress. 
<p>	"Congress never sanctioned the discriminatory conduct that now occurs routinely in the American workplace under the rubric of 'affirmative action,'" says Lund. "In fact, group-based employment preferences are incompatible with the ideal of equal opportunity that every federal employment statute has claimed to advance." Rather, the system of  race-based preferences now in place was imposed by unelected federal regulators and rogue judges who took it upon themselves to interpret the "color-blindness" of Title VII in a perverse manner that developed into the very opposite of color-blindness. 
<p>	But it is not enough for Congress to proclaim now that it meant what it said 31 years ago. Congress should also prohibit "backdoor quotas" that discriminate through terms like "diversity," "inclusiveness," and "multiculturalism," according to Lund. "The existing cast of bureaucrats and corporate affirmative action officers should be forbidden from repackaging the same old surreptitious racial quotas under some new rubric like 'socially disadvantaged background,'" he says. "Any legislation adopted by Congress must contain airtight legislative language that closes the door to the use of new euphemisms and new rationales for discrimination," he says.
<P>	Legitimate affirmative action programs that promote equal opportunity without relying upon or encouraging the use of race or sex-based quotas or preferences should be allowed to continue. This would ensure that "minorities and women are not excluded from employment opportunities by managers' prejudices, stereotypes, or inappropriate recruiting habits," Lund says.
<p>	Congressional action is needed, Lund says, because of President Clinton's recent decision to "strongly reaffirm the federal government's long-standing and thoroughly discredited approach" to affirmative action. That approach is easy to sum up, he says: "Proclaim a fervid opposition to discrimination, but practice a policy of discriminatory preferences and favoritism for selected groups."
<p>	Clinton's position is also contrary to that of the Progressive Policy Institute (PPI), a think tank that has been supportive of the administration in the past but which recently suggested phasing out affirmative action programs in federal hiring and contracting, and making it voluntary throughout the private sector, except on college campuses. 
<p>	Yet, the Clinton approach has caused immense public controversy and outcry against affirmative action. For example, Lund cites federal court decisions holding, that:
<ul>
<li>	 A county agency could deny a promotion to a male and instead promote a less qualified female as part of an affirmative action plan requiring that 36.4 percent (the court-determined percentage of women in the county workforce) of the county's highway maintenance crews be female. This, "despite the utterly obvious fact that women are less likely than men to seek jobs involving heavy physical labor."
<li>	 A fire department could deny a promotion to a white firefighter who received the highest score on a competitive exam and instead promote a black firefighter with a lower score. 
<li>	 A university sociology department could discriminate against male applicants for teaching positions because sociology has to be "considered a traditionally segregated field" as long as half the nation's population is women but only 34 percent of the sociology doctorates are awarded to women.
</ul><p>	Passage of legislation to put an end to such applications of the law "would extend the principle of equal treatment under the law to the more than 94 million American employees now covered by the 1964 Civil Rights Act," Lund says. "There is no longer any need nor justification for compromise, incremental changes or further temporizing" on the affirmative action issue.				
<p>
Note: Professor Lund can be reached at (703) 993-8045
<p>
Note: All Heritage Foundation papers are now available electronically to subscribers to the "NEXIS" on-line data-retrieval service. The Heritage Foundation's Reports (HFRPTS) can be found in the OMNI, CURRNT, NWLTRS, and GVT group files of the NEXIS library and the GOVT and OMNI group files of the GOVNWS library.
