<html>
<title>
<Press Release: Overhauling Superfund</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>
News Release</h2>
<hr>
<i><b><a href="http://www.townhall.com/heritage/">The Heritage Foundation</a></b><br>
214 Massachusetts Avenue, NE<br>
Washington, D.C. 20002<br>
(202) 546-4400</i>
<hr>
<h3>
<b>CLEANING UP SUPERFUND MEANS<br> 
COMPLETE OVERHAUL, ANALYST SAYS<br></b></b>   
States Should be Given More Control<br>
<p></h3><br>
</center><b>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
<p>
WASHINGTON, AUG. 4, 1995  --</b>  As Congress prepares to reauthorize the 1980 Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and  Liability Act (CERCLA), popularly known as "Superfund," it must correct fundamental flaws and not merely tinker with the statute, a Heritage Foundation analyst said today.  
<p>
"Reform should address the core elements of the Superfund structure that fuel litigation, slow cleanups, raise costs and, most important, encourage the cleanup of sites that pose little risk to human health and safety, and divert scarce economic resources from sites that may pose real dangers," according to Environmental Policy Analyst <a href="http://www.townhall.com/heritage/staff/shanahan.htm">John Shanahan</a>.
<p>
Created by the Carter administration in 1980 to clean up the nation's worst hazardous waste sites, the Superfund program "has spent between $20 billion and $30 billion and has failed to clean up more than a small fraction of these sites," Shanahan says. "Even the Clinton administration admits the program does not work."
<p>
 Shanahan says Congress must make the following changes in the Superfund law:
<ul>
<li>Establish priorities for which hazardous waste sites pose the greatest risk to human health and clean up those sites first. "According to the Office of Technology Assessment, the listing of most Superfund sites is based on hypothetical rather than actual or likely future risks," Shanahan says. "The Superfund law aims at cleaning up spilled chemicals, regardless of  whether  these pose an immediate danger. The result: Money and effort have been squandered that could have been used elsewhere to save more lives."  
<p>
<li>Stop requiring waste sites to be cleaned up to a pristine level no matter what the location. "Polluted soil at industrial park sites must be cleaned up to a level that makes it essentially clean enough to eat," said Shanahan. "An industrial park does not need to be as pristine as a playground. Once again, priorities must be established so public safety is maximized, while scarce resources are not wasted." 
<p>
<li>Get rid of Superfund's liability scheme, which is "designed to find somebody -- anybody -- to pay for cleanup of hazardous waste," even if the "responsible" person or party had only a tiny part in creating the waste problem, or disposed of waste in a manner that was legal at the time but which became illegal under the Superfund law, Shanahan says. In practice, this often means a firm with "deep pockets" ends up paying for the cleanup of wastes created by someone else. "Naturally, any person or institution identified as a polluter has a strong incentive to show that others are liable as well, in order to spread the costs among more parties. Litigation is virtually assured," which consumes enormous amounts of time and money, delaying cleanup of hundreds of sites. Instead, Shanahan says, "Reform would make clear that liability is proportional to a party's contribution to the level of pollution at a waste site."
<p>
<li>Make hazardous waste cleanup a local, instead of a federal responsibility. "Unlike most all other major environmental laws, responsibility for Superfund is not delegated to the states. Yet, hazardous waste sites, are at their core, a local problem. State and local officials are far more accountable for local risks under their control than are distant federal officials," Shanahan says. "Authority for cleanup of hazardous waste sites should be turned over to the states -- with the necessary funding. To qualify for funds, states should be required to prioritize sites and expenditures based on real risks." 
</ul>
<p>
In addition to these reforms, Shanahan says the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)</a> should retain emergency cleanup capacity. "The EPA is both experienced and relatively efficient at emergency responses to truly hazardous waste problems. Therefore, it should maintain this capacity, with states deciding whether a site constitutes an emergency. Costs would be recovered from the state or the party responsible for polluting the site," he says.
<BR><HR WIDTH="30%"><BR><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER></body>
</html>
