<html>
<title> Press Release: Privatizing Adoption -- Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>News Release</h2>
<hr>
<i><b><A HREf="http://www.townhall.com/heritage/">The Heritage Foundation</a></b><br>
214 Massachusetts Avenue, NE<br>
Washington, D.C. 20002<br>
(202) 546-4400</i>
<hr>
<h3>WELFARE REFORM SHOULD INCLUDE<BR>
PRIVATIZING ADOPTION, ANALYST SAYS</h3>
<p></center><BR>
<b>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</B>
<P>
<b>WASHINGTON, AUG. 2, 1995 --</b> The only way for nearly half a million foster children to become available to more than 2 million couples who would like to adopt them is for states to take adoption away from the public welfare bureaucracy and give it back to the private sector, according to a Heritage Foundation analyst.
<p>
"The $10 billion-per-year foster-care and adoption system in this country has become a major obstacle keeping thousands of children from being united with loving parents," says Heritage FitzGerald Senior Fellow <a href="http://www.townhall.com/heritage/staff/fagan.htm">Patrick Fagan</a>, a former family therapist and clinical psychologist, in a paper released today.  "The anti-adoption bias of the current public-sector welfare bureaucracy has resulted in an adoption process with too many built-in obstacles. These obstacles feed children into the foster-care system and keep them there, ensuring a larger clientele for public agencies, at a staggering emotional cost," he says. 
<p>
Yet, Fagan says, "Adoption benefits all involved. It increases the emotional, physical and cognitive capacities of children, and increases the life chances of the biological mother." What's more, if adoption is made quicker and easier, it will ease the burden America will feel by 2012, when a 50 percent out-of-wedlock birthrate is expected to vastly increase the number of abused and neglected children. "Serious welfare reform, therefore, must include serious adoption reform," Fagan believes.
<p>
Fagan says private adoption services are more efficient and effective than state agencies. "They are accountable to boards of directors, while state agencies are not. Private organizations can be sued, which increases their accountability to the children and parents they serve." For these and other reasons, Fagan believes "The quickest, simplest solution is for states, which have primary responsibility for regulating adoption, to place the job of finding suitable parents in the hands of private adoption services. Both state and federal lawmakers can work in tandem to facilitate this process," he says.
<p>
While significant, Fagan says the tax credit for adoptive parents recently passed by the House of Representatives as part of its welfare-reform bill will not lead to a major increase in adoption unless the almost insurmountable barriers to adoption erected by the social service bureaucracy are removed. 
<p>
He says, for example, that a significant part of the reason only 1 percent of women choose adoption as a solution to their unwanted pregnancies is lack of information. "Some 40 percent of pregnancy counselors don't even raise the issue of adoption with pregnant clients; another 40 percent provide incomplete or inaccurate information about adoption," Fagan says. Yet, when adoption is mentioned, 38 percent choose it rather than alternatives like abortion.
<p>
Race is another barrier/bias in the adoption system, Fagan says. Even though a higher proportion of black than white children are available to adopt, and even though many white parents would like to adopt black children, the welfare bureaucracy is dedicated to a policy of "race matching," which delays adoption for years, and many times prevents black children from ever being placed in a loving home. This phenomenon occurs in the other direction as well, though not as often. As a result, "black children typically wait two to three years longer than white children for adoptive homes." 
<p>
To fix these and other problems, Fagan suggests a number of reforms, the majority of which must take place at the state level. For example, besides privatizing all adoption services, he says states should:
<ul>
<p>
<li>Remove obstacles to transracial adoptions.
<p>
<li>Enact a strict 12-month timeline for working out the long-term parental status of any child in foster care.
<p>
<li>Separate the responsibility for protecting children from convicted abusive parents from that of preserving parental rights for families that can be helped. "Professionals should not be trapped between simultaneous demands to reunite every family and to protect every child. When these duties are separated, both goals are better served," Fagan says.
<p>
<li>Prohibit the removal of a child from foster parents willing to adopt him or her, except when the child is being returned to its legal parents.
</ul>
<p>
In addition, Fagan says Congress should: 	
<ul>
<p>
<li>Enact a means-tested, fully refundable, inflation-adjusted tax credit of up to $5,000 to help pay the substantial one-time costs incurred by adoptive parents. 
<p>
<li>Require hospitals and clinics receiving federal aid to provide timely and accurate adoption information to all mothers who give birth out of wedlock.
<p>
<li>Prohibit the use of race or ethnicity to deny or delay placement of a child in foster care or adoption.
</ul>
<p>
Fagan's views are movingly reinforced in the latest issue of Policy Review, Heritage's quarterly journal, by "John," a baseball-loving 10-year-old who has been waiting almost his entire life for a family: "I'm all wrapped up in programs, what I need is a mom." John is quoted in an <a href="http://www.townhall.com/heritage/p_review/summer95/thcraig.htm">article written by Conna Craig</a>, a former foster child and president of the Cambridge, Massachusetts-based Institute for Children.
<p>
"The problem," Craig says, "is a system that gives child welfare bureaucracies incentives to keep even free-to-be-adopted kids in state care, an anti-adoption bias that creates numerous legal and regulatory barriers, and a culture of victimization that places the whims of irresponsible parents above the well-being of their children." State social-service agencies are neither rewarded for helping children find adoptive homes, nor penalized for failing to do so in a reasonable amount of time, Craig says.
<p>
"As one foster child put it: 'Everywhere I go, somebody gets money to keep me from having a mom and dad," she says.
<p>

<BR><HR WIDTH="30%"><BR><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER> 
</body>
</html>
