<H3>For Immediate Release</H3>
<BR>
<B>Contact: Heritage Public Relations</B>
<P>
<U><B>Part of the new &quot;Town Hall&quot;</B></U>
<P>
<B>HERITAGE FOUNDATION DEBUTS ON INTERNET</B>
<P>
<B> WASHINGTON, JUNE 29, 1995 --  </B>The Heritage Foundation
will open its World Wide Web site on the Internet today, making
its research and policy papers accessible to millions around the
world.
<P>
 Conservatives and others cruising the information superhighway
will find the Heritage site at http://www.heritage.org. There,
they will be able to access staff biographies, forums where they
can discuss the latest political news with policy experts, policy
research and commentary and membership information.
<P>
 With more than 200,000 members and supporters, Heritage currently
is the most broadly supported think tank in the United States.
<P>
 &quot;Heritage is using the latest technology to promote conservative
ideas on a global scale,&quot; said Edwin J. Feulner Jr., Heritage
Foundation president. He said many people are now &quot;going
around&quot; the traditional print and broadcast media for political
information and find the Internet a convenient way to access information
that hasn't been through &quot;the filtering process of the mainstream
media.&quot;
<P>
 The Heritage Web site -- part of the broader Town Hall Internet
community -- will offer browsers the latest in full-text searching
using a &quot;key word&quot; or phrase.
<P>
 The Web site's official opening will be held at 11 a.m. at the
Capitol Hill Club, 300 First St., S.E. Town Hall is owned jointly
by Heritage and National Review. On hand for the opening will
be Feulner, Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., and National
Review Editor John O'Sullivan.
<P>
