<html>
<title>Tax Reform NOW! -- Flat Tax Rate Bibliography</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>[<a href="experts.html">Experts</a>][<a href="welcome.html">Home</a>][<a href="links.html">Links</a>][<a href="http://www.townhall.com">Town Hall</a>]<p>
<img src="tr-now2.gif" width=300 height=90 border=0 alt="Tax Reform NOW! logo">
<br>
<h1><font color="blue">FLAT RATE TAX BIBLIOGRAPHY</font></h1>

Compiled by <a href="mailto:73440.3456@compuserve.com">Bruce Bartlett</a><br>
<a href="http://www.public-policy.org/~ncpa/">National Center for Policy Analysis</a>
<P>
<hr>
<p>

Sources listed alphabetically by author, use <a name="quick">QuickLinks</a> to navigate through alphabet, or scroll through entire document. <p>

[ <a href="#A">A-C</a> ] &nbsp &nbsp  [ <a href="#D">D-G</a> ] &nbsp &nbsp  [ <a href="#H">H-K</a> ] &nbsp &nbsp  [ <a href="#L">L-O</a> ] &nbsp &nbsp  [ <a href="#P">P-R</a> ] &nbsp &nbsp  [ <a href="#S">S-V</a> ] &nbsp &nbsp  [ <a href="#W">W-Z</a> ]
</center>
<p><p>


<hr>
<a name="A"></a>A-C<p>



Aaron, Henry J. 1982.  "Toward Fairer Taxation."  <i>New York Times</i>  (September 26).
<blockquote>
          Opposes pure flat rate tax, but favors rate reduction
          and base-broadening.
</blockquote><p>
Altig, David, and Charles T. Carlstrom. 1994.  "The Efficiency and Welfare Effects of Tax Reform: Are Fewer Brackets Better than More?"  <i>Economic Review</i>, Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland, vol. 30, no. 4 (4th Quarter), pp. 30-42.
<blockquote>
          Finds that a pure flat rate tax is preferable to a
          modified flat rate system.
</blockquote><p>
Armey, Richard K. 1994a.  "Review Merits of Flat Tax."  <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (June 16).
<p>
Armey, Richard K. 1994b.  "The Flat Tax: Restoring Freedom and Fairness."  <i>Commonsense</i> (Fall), pp. 48-54.
<p>
Auerbach, Alan J., Laurence Kotlikoff, and Jonathan Skinner. 1983.  "The Efficiency Gains from Dynamic Tax Reform."  <i>International Economic Review</i>, vol. 24, no. 1 (February), pp. 81-100.
<blockquote>
          Finds large efficiency gains from switching to a
          proportional, consumption-based tax system.  Also finds
          large efficiency costs from even small degrees of
          progressivity.
</blockquote><p>
Ballard, Charles L., John B. Shoven, and John Whalley. 1985a.  "General Equilibrium Computations of the Marginal Welfare Costs of Taxes in the United States."  <i>American Economic
     Review</i>, vol. 75, no. 1 (March), pp. 128-138.
<blockquote>
          Finds that the excess burden of the U.S. tax system is
          as much as 56% of tax revenue.
</blockquote><p>
Ballard, Charles L., John B. Shoven, and John Whalley. 1985b.  "The Total Welfare Cost of the United States Tax System: A General Equilibrium Approach." <i>National Tax Journal</i>, vol.
     38, no. 2 (June), pp. 125-140.
<blockquote>
          Finds large welfare gains from eliminating distortions
          in the U.S. tax system and replacing it with a
          consumption-based system.
</blockquote><p>
Bankman, Joseph, and Thomas Griffith. 1987.  "Social Welfare and
     the Rate Structure: A New Look at Progressive Taxation." 
     <i>California Law Review</i>, vol. 75, no. 6 (December), pp. 1905-
1967.
<blockquote>
          Two professors of law at the University of Southern
          California support progressivity, but oppose graduated
          tax rates.  They favor achieving redistribution through
          income transfers rather than taxation.
</blockquote><p>
Bartlett, Bruce. 1978.  "The Economics of Progressive Taxation." 
     <i>Modern Age</i>, vol. 22, no. 3 (Summer), pp. 285-292.
<blockquote>
          Presents a comprehensive set of arguments against
          progressivity.
</blockquote><p>
Bartlett, Bruce. 1986.  "Federal Income Tax Reform: Resuming the
     Battle."  <i>Backgrounder</i> No. 554, <a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a>
     (December 30).
<blockquote>
