Epstein, Richard A. 1986.  "Taxation in a Lockean World."  <i>Social
     Philosophy and Policy</i>, vol. 4, no. 1 (Autumn), pp. 49-74.
<blockquote>
          Argues that in principle people should be taxed exactly
          according to the benefits they receive from government. 
          Since, as a practical matter, it is impossible to
          precisely measure each individual's government
          benefits, a low flat-rate system is a close
          approximation of an ideal tax.
</blockquote><p>
