Hayek, F.A. 1956.  "Progressive Taxation Reconsidered."  In Mary
     Sennholz, ed., <i>On Freedom and Free Enterprise</i>.  Princeton:
     D. Van Nostrand, pp. 265-284.
<blockquote>
          Favors setting the top marginal tax rate at a level
          equal to the overall level of taxation as a share of
          GNP.  (Thus if federal taxes constituted 20% of GNP,
          then the maximum marginal tax rate would be 20%.)
</blockquote><p>
Henderson, Yolanda K. 1988.  "Further Base Broadening: A Possible
     Source of Tax Revenues?"  <i>New England Economic Review</i>,
     Federal Reserve Bank of Boston (March/April), pp. 33-45.
<blockquote>
          Although the Tax Reform Act of 1986 eliminated many
          deductions and exclusion from the tax code, many still
          remain.  Elimination of these items could still be a
          large potential source of revenue to the government. 
          See also Bartlett (1986).
</blockquote><p>
Hitchens, Christopher. 1994.  "Minority Report."  <i>The Nation</i> (December 12), p. 716.
<blockquote>
          Prominent Leftist favors a flat tax because it "would
          eliminate the parasitic class of taxfixers who exempt
          the rich and the corporations from their fair share,
          and also eliminate the pulverizing bureaucracy which
          keeps people in permanent, servile confusion about
          whether or not they have complied with the law."  See
          also Cockburn and Pollin (1992).
</blockquote><p>
Horrigan, Brian R. 1985.  "The Tax Reform Controversy: A Guide for the Perplexed."  <i>Business Review</i>, Federal Reserve Bank
     of Philadelphia (May-June), pp. 3-15.
<blockquote>
          Believes that flat-rate tax would lead to large
          economic efficiency gains, but raises concern about
          distributional issues.
</blockquote><p>
Hoven, Vernon. 1995.  "Flat Tax as Seen by a Tax Preparer."  <i>Tax
     Notes</i>, vol. 68, no. 6 (August 7), pp. 747-755.
<p>
Hunter, William J., and Charles E. Scott. 1987.  "The Impact of Income Tax Progressivity on Tax Revenue."  <i>Public Finance Quarterly</i>, vol. 15, no 2 (April), pp. 188-198.
<blockquote>
          The authors find a negative relationship between state
          income tax receipts and the progressivity of their
          income tax systems.  Consequently, adoption of flat-
rate taxes at the state level would probably increase
          revenues.
</blockquote><p>
Jastram, Roy W. 1983.  "Flat-Tax Lab: The Isle of Man."  <i>Wall Street Journal</i> (January 28).
